<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06353163 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06353163 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; HOCKEY; GAME; RESULT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Calgary Flames scored five goals early in the third period to defeat thevisiting Winnipeg Jets 7-4 Tuesday.;   The outburst came in a span of 4minutes, 55 seconds. Ron Stern got two of the goals. Also scoring for Calgaryin the spurt were Gary Roberts, Joel Otto and Doug Gilmour with his second ofthe game.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FLAMES ERUPT ALL OVER JETSCALGARY SCORES 5 GOALS IN 4:55  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     After the fourth goal, by Gilmour at 7:01 that put the Flames ahead 6-4,Winnipeg pulled goalie Stephane Beauregard and sent in Mike O'Neill. O'Neillwas beaten on the first shot against him, by Stern.;   Beauregard and O'Neillfaced 41 shots, while Calgary's Rick Wamsley faced 22.; CANUCKS 2, RED WINGS1: Garry Valk scored the winning goal in the second period as host Vancouverhanded Detroit only its second loss in 19 games.;   The Canucks killed offthree penalties in the third period.;   Vancouver goalie Kirk McLean was sharpin the third and the penalty-killers were even quicker when the Canucks deniedDetroit a goal during the five-minute penalty to Valk for slashing SergeiFedorov.;   The crowd of 15,609 gave the Canucks a standing ovation after GregAdams nearly scored a shorthanded goal against Detroit goalie Tim Cheveldae.;  Steve Chiasson scored for the Red Wings in the second period and was involvedin a controversial play in the third.;   Referee Mike McGeough disallowed aDetroit goal, ruling that Ray Sheppard used his glove to redirect a shot byChiasson during a Detroit power play.; NORTH STARS 2, KINGS 1: DefensemanDerian Hatcher, in his final game before sitting out a 10-game suspension,scored his fifth goal of the season as Minnesota beat Los Angeles and snappedan eight-game winless streak in Inglewood.;   Darcy Wakaluk, making his sixthstart in goal, stopped 32 shots to lead the defending Campbell Conferencechamps to their first victory on the Kings' rink since Jan. 23, 1987.;CAPITALS 3, NORDIQUES 1: Dino Ciccarelli scored two power-play goals to leadWashington over Quebec in Landover, Md., keeping the Nordiques winless on theroad.;   The Nordiques, the only team in the NHL without a road victory thisseason, are 0-12-2 away from from Le Colisee. The Nordiques have not won in 16straight road games dating to last season.;   Ciccarelli scored his sixth andseventh power-play goals of the season -- his 18th and 19th overall -- in thesecond period.;   Quebec goalie Ron Tugnutt, 0-7-0 on the road, made 29saves.; ISLANDERS 4, WHALERS 2: Benoit Hogue scored two goals as New Yorkscored four straight times in Hartford, Conn.;   Hogue scored a fluke goal3:33 into the third period to give the Islanders their first lead. JeffFinley's slap shot from the left point missed the net, but the puck bounced toHogue at the right of the net and he lifted a shot that banked in off goaliePeter Sidorkiewicz's glove.; ETC.: The Hartford Whalers, one of whose ownerswas forced into bankruptcy, are staying put, NHL President John Ziegler said.Ziegler said he called the Hartford Courant because he was concerned overrumors circulating about the team.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911218  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  523  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, December 18, 199100353163,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>